split the original testing dataset into training and testing

Corr plot

library(corrplot)
cor <- cor(testing[,-54])
corrplot(cor, type = "lower", method = "square", cl.pos = "b", tl.cex=.6)

Remove predictors with extremely high corellation (>= 0.9)

hc <- findCorrelation(cor, cutoff = 0.9, verbose = TRUE)
## Compare row 11  and column  2 with corr  0.992 
##   Means:  0.272 vs 0.17 so flagging column 11 
## Compare row 2  and column  10 with corr  0.929 
##   Means:  0.254 vs 0.166 so flagging column 2 
## Compare row 10  and column  5 with corr  0.931 
##   Means:  0.236 vs 0.163 so flagging column 10 
## Compare row 9  and column  3 with corr  0.965 
##   Means:  0.254 vs 0.16 so flagging column 9 
## Compare row 20  and column  19 with corr  0.92 
##   Means:  0.093 vs 0.16 so flagging column 19 
## All correlations <= 0.9
training <- training[,-hc]

Cross validation

K-fold cross validation with k = 10 will be used

fitCtrl <- trainControl(method = "cv", number = 10)

Classification And Regression Tree approach with PCA

set.seed(123321)
fitTree <- train(classe ~ ., data = training, method = "rpart", preProcess = "pca", trControl = fitCtrl)
fitTree

## read testing data
theTestData <- read.csv("pml-testing.csv", header = TRUE, na.strings = c("NA", "", "#DIV/0!"))
theTestData <- theTestData[, colSums(is.na(theTestData)) == 0]

tt <- tbl_df(theTestData)
tt <- tt[, !grepl("X|timestamp|new_window|user_name", names(tt))]
